Que 22) What are HTML Attributes? What are the Types of HTML attributes?
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
HTML attributes provide additional information about an HTML element.
They are written inside the opening tag and usually come as name="value" pairs.
Example:
<a href="https://example.com">Visit</a>
Here href is the attribute and https://example.com
 is its value.
Types of HTML Attributes:
Global Attributes – Can be used with almost all HTML elements (example: id, class, style, title).
Specific Attributes – Used only with certain elements (example: href for <a>, src for <img>, type for <input>).
Que 23) What are the Id, Style & Class attributes of an element? When to use what?
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
id attribute → Gives a unique name to an element. Used for JavaScript or CSS targeting.
class attribute → Used to group multiple elements so the same CSS style can be applied.
style attribute → Used to apply inline CSS directly to an element.
Example:
<p id="title" class="text" style="color:red;">Hello</p>
When to use:
Use id → when the element must be unique.
Use class → when many elements share the same style.
Use style → for quick inline styling.
Que 24) What will happen if two elements have same ids?
------------------------------------------------------
If two elements have the same id, it breaks HTML rules because id must be unique.
Problems that may occur:
JavaScript may select only the first element.
CSS targeting may not work correctly.
It can cause unexpected behavior in the webpage.
Que 25) How to specify Multiple Classes for single element? What is the style precedence?
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
You can add multiple classes by separating them with spaces.
Example:
<p class="red bold large">Hello</p>
Style precedence (priority order):
1️⃣ Inline style (style="") – Highest priority
2️⃣ ID selector (#id)
3️⃣ Class selector (.class)
4️⃣ Element selector (p, div) – Lowest priority
